# Balatro Guide

Balatro is a roguelike deck-building game where you play poker hands to score points and defeat blinds (score targets). You collect Jokers that modify scoring rules, enhance cards with special abilities, and strategically build synergies to reach exponentially higher scores.

The game alternates between a four main game phases:

1. **Blind Select Phase**: You decide to play or skip the next round (aka blind). If you play and win the blind, you earn money and have access to the shop Phase. If you skip, you won't earn money rewarded for winning a blind, you won't have access to the shop and you will be send to the next Blind Select Phase. However you will gain a Tag, a special item that activate its effect in the next blind played. You can accumulate Tags for consecutive skips (effects of accumulated tags will all activate in the next blind played).

2. **Playing Phase**: You start with a initial hand of 8 cards. You play a limited number of pokers-like hands (hands left) which scores points according to the scoring system. Scores for the played hands sum together into the current score in order to reach the score target for the round. Under normal circumstances, you can play up to 5 cards at once. You have also access to a limited number of discards (discard left) where you can discard, under normal circumstances, up to 5 cards. In the case of a discard, you will draw from the deck the same amount of cards you have discarded and those cards are added to your current hand. By strategically discard useless cards, you will have a chance to draw new cards that help you creating high scoring hands. If you successfully reach the target score, you will proceed to the Round Eval Phase otherwise it's Game Over.

3. **Round Eval Phase**: In this phase you collect the rewards money for winning the previous round. The money rewarded is proportional to the number of hands left at the end of the round (1$ each). You can receive also interest money ($1 per $5, max 5$). Then you enter the Shop Phase.

4. **Shop Phase**: You can buy jokers, consumables, packs, cards, and vouchers to modify the scoring system. The objective in this phase is to strategically use (or not use) the shop action to strategically invest (or save) money to upgrade the scoring system for the following rounds. After you have perform all the action you want to perform in the shop, you can proceed to the next Blind Select Phase (next round).

## Initial Setup

When starting a new run, players begin with $4, a standard 52-card deck (13 ranks across 4 suits), 5 empty Joker slots, and 2 consumable slots. Each round provides 4 hands and 3 discards as the baseline to defeat blinds. Players draw 8 cards at the start of each round. The economic system rewards $1 per unspent hand after defeating a blind, plus $1 interest per $5 saved (maximum $5 interest at $25+). The first Ante requires 300 chips for the Small Blind, 450 for the Big Blind, and 600 for the Boss Blind.

## Blinds and Antes

Blinds are the main obstacle that the player must overcome during a run in Balatro. For each selected Blind, the player has to meet or surpass the required score to beat it, otherwise they will lose their run. Defeating the Blind may earn some reward money as well.

An Ante is made up of three Blinds in succession: a Small Blind, a Big Blind, and a random Boss Blind. Special Boss Blinds called Showdown Blinds only appear on the final level of a run, at Ante 8. The player can choose to take on a Small or Big Blind, or to skip one or both and claim one or more Tags instead; Boss Blinds must always be played.

You start at Ante 1 and go up an Ante level for every Boss Blind defeated. By completing Ante 8 and finishing the Showdown Blind, the run is considered "won".

### Small Blind and Big Blind

Small and Big Blinds have no other effects and can be skipped to receive a Tag.

### Boss Blinds

Boss Blinds are the last blind of an Ante. Boss Blinds have certain special effects that add difficulty to the round, for example:

- Debuffing some category of cards. The debuffed cards, appearing with a red cross, can still make Poker Hands but won't be scored.

- Causing some cards to be drawn face-down, making them entirely hidden before being played. A hand played including face-down cards will have its type displayed as "???"; scoring and other effects will still perform as normal.

- Restricting the size or type of poker hand that can be played. Hands that don't meet the restriction can still be played, but will not be scored or activate other effects, acting like a discard.

Boss Blinds are randomly selected.

Showdown Blinds are a special type of Boss Blind, that appear at the end of the game (Ante 8) and are identical to regular Boss Blinds.

